# AKOS SSOT Registry Audit + Canonical Touch Discipline

Use when creating, editing, or wiring **vault canonicals** and their **registry
rows**. Pairs with [`ssot-canonical-touch-craft`](../skills/ssot-canonical-touch-craft/SKILL.md)
and [`akos-operator-communication.mdc`](akos-operator-communication.mdc) RULE 4.

Vault doctrine: [`SSOT_REGISTRY_AUDIT_DISCIPLINE.md`](../../docs/references/hlk/v3.0/Admin/O5-1/Data/Governance/canonicals/SSOT_REGISTRY_AUDIT_DISCIPLINE.md).

## RULE 1 — Four-registry lens on every mint (binding)

When a new or updated artifact lands in `docs/references/hlk/v3.0/`, run the
**same quality exercise** against the four SSOT maps the operator uses to see
the whole estate:

| Registry | Functional role | Typical action |
|:---|:---|:---|
| `PRECEDENCE.md` | Audit trail + human index | Row when doctrine is SSOT |
| `CANONICAL_REGISTRY.csv` | Artifact inventory (T1) | Row per active canonical path |
| `CANONICAL_RELATIONSHIP_REGISTRY.csv` | How types link (HCAM) | Triple when new composition/serving pattern |
| `CANONICAL_GOVERNANCE_REGISTRY.csv` | CSV/mirror Plane-1/2 only | Row **only** for CSV surfaces — not markdown |

`CANONICAL_ARTICULATION_MODEL.md` is the metamodel; update when the wiring
pattern itself changes. `ENTITY_CATALOG.csv` changes only for net-new entity
types (rare).

One area mint (e.g. Research Methodology) is a **worked example**, not the
whole job. Schedule **area-by-area** sweeps so PRECEDENCE-only rows do not
linger without `CANONICAL_REGISTRY` inventory.

## RULE 2 — Ask before vault touch; balance with encouragement (binding)

The operator wants agents to **ask before touching canonicals** — and also wants
canonical work to **keep moving**. Use this tier model:

| Tier | Paths | Gate |
|:---|:---|:---|
| **A — Vault + canonical CSV** | `docs/references/hlk/v3.0/**/canonicals/**`, `PRECEDENCE.md`, `process_list.csv`, `baseline_organisation.csv`, `CANONICAL_REGISTRY.csv`, capability/compliance dimension CSVs | **`AskQuestion` before first write** in the session unless operator explicitly said mint/commit/go ahead **for that scope** in the same turn |
| **B — WIP intelligence** | `docs/wip/intelligence/**` | Lighter gate: proceed when task is research ingest; AskQuestion before promoting to vault |
| **C — Code + tests** | `akos/`, `scripts/`, `tests/` | Follow normal phase discipline; no extra canonical gate |

**Balance (do not over-ask):**

- Operator says "mint", "go ahead", "commit", or answers an `AskQuestion` with
  approve → **that scope is ratified**; execute without re-asking the same gate.
- Bundle related vault files in **one** AskQuestion (discipline + SOP + registry
  rows), not six sequential gates.
- **Do ask** when scope expands (e.g. extra CSV tranche, PRECEDENCE + process_list
  + new doctrine) or when touching Tier A was not part of the operator's request.

## RULE 3 — Prose register for canonicals and operator summaries (binding)

Canonicals are read by **J-OP** (you) and executed by **J-AIC** (agents).

When authoring or summarising:

1. Lead with **what now works** in plain language (see operator-communication
   RULE 1–2).
2. Avoid **mechanical audit voice**: dense DONE/N/A tables, identifier chains
   without functional names, triadic abstract-noun stacks, contrastive
   "X, not Y" cadence.
3. SOPs and disciplines: write steps a colleague would follow; validators and
   IDs attach **after** the human-readable core.
4. Apply **Impeccable copywriting** tic avoidance even for internal prose —
   see [`BRAND_COPYWRITING_DISCIPLINE.md`](../../docs/references/hlk/v3.0/Admin/O5-1/Marketing/Brand/Copywriter/canonicals/BRAND_COPYWRITING_DISCIPLINE.md).
5. Audience tags in frontmatter: `J-OP` for operator narrative; `J-AIC` for
   executable instruction surfaces (paired SOPs, cursor rules, runbooks).

## RULE 4 — Commit gate (binding)

Tier A changes that will land in git: **`AskQuestion` before commit** unless
operator already ratified commit in the same thread. Never commit canonical CSVs
without explicit operator approval per baseline governance.

